Part 7

The chair came with the office, which was really just two rooms above a spare-parts godown that the company had converted because nothing better was available yet in this city.

Brown leatherette, cracked along both arms, one wheel that stuck slightly and made the whole chair list two degrees left if you weren't careful standing up.

Vikram's second manager here, a sharp young man named Suresh, had tried twice to get it replaced.

"Sir, we can order a proper executive chair. Company budget allows for it easily."

"This one works."

"It's falling apart, sir."

"It hasn't fallen apart yet."

Suresh gave up after the second attempt, filing his boss under the general category of eccentric men he didn't need to understand to work for.

---

Vikram sat in it the night the first factory workers' wage dispute came to his desk — eleven men, three months unpaid because a regional distributor had defaulted and the company's own cash was tied up in the land deal that still hadn't cleared.

He could have waited. Legally, he had grounds to wait.

He sat in the cracked chair until past midnight going through the numbers twice, found a way to release partial payment from a different account by morning, and told Suresh to arrange it before the workers even arrived to ask.

"That's not how the process usually works, sir."

"I know."

"Head office will ask questions."

"Let them ask."

He sat in it again three weeks later, the night a second factory's water-supply request needed approval that would cost the company more than the state government would ever reimburse, and he approved it anyway, because the alternative was six hundred families carrying water two kilometers by hand indefinitely while paperwork moved through channels designed to move slowly.

---

"Why not just replace it," Reddy asked once, visiting the office and eyeing the chair with open disapproval. "It looks like something waiting to collapse."

"Because it doesn't let me forget."

"Forget what?"

Vikram didn't answer immediately, running one thumb along the cracked arm the way another man might touch a scar to check it was still there.

"Every time I sit in something comfortable, I start making comfortable decisions. This one reminds me every few minutes that it could give way. Keeps me honest about what's actually at stake when I sign something."

Reddy looked at him for a long moment, the way a man looks at someone he's revising an old opinion about.

He didn't say anything about it then.

He would, eventually — but that conversation belonged to a different night, a different pot of tea, still some weeks away.

For now, the chair held, listing its two degrees left, and Vikram kept signing what needed signing, one cracked-leather night at a time.
